When I consider life, 'tis all a cheat3

Yet, fool'd with hope, men favour the deceit, Trust on, and think to-morrow will repayt To-morrow’s falser than the sonner day,

Lies worse3 and while it says, we shall he bless'd With some new joys, cuts off what we possessed. Strange coz'nage! none would live past years again, Yet all hope pleasure in what yet remeia,

And from the dregs of life think to receive What the first sprightly running could not give. I’m tired with waiting for this chymic gold, Which fools us young, and beggars us when old.
